# Intuition 
There are many ways to solve this problem so i'm going to show two solutions
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->

# 1. Iterative
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the pcroblem. -->

The first approach is iteration, how does it work?- first we compare the last character in the array with our target char if the last character is less than  target it means there is no element which is greater than target(because our array is in non-decreasing order), so we just return the first element of the array.
    e.x: letters = ["a","b","c","d"], target = "e"
    we compare the last element of array which is `d`, `d`<`e`, sowe  should return `a`.
If the last character is not less than or equal to the target we iterate the array untill we find the answer.



# Complexity
- Time complexity: `O(N)`
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
- Space complexity:`O(1)`
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
# Code
```
class Solution {
    public char nextGreatestLetter(char[] letters, char target) {
        if(letters[letters.length - 1] <= target) return letters[0]; //no need to iterate whole array

        for (char letter : letters) {
            if (letter > target) {
                return letter;
            }
        }
        //just return smth
        return letters[0];
    }
}
```
# 2. Binary Search
 This approach is more optimal than the first one because time complexity is `O(logN)`. I tried to explain it with comments.

# Complexity
- Time complexity: `O(logN)`
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity:`O(1)`
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
# Code
```
class Solution {
    public char nextGreatestLetter(char[] letters, char target) {
        int left = 0;
        int right = letters.length - 1;

        while(left < right) {
            int mid = (left + right) / 2;

            if(letters[mid] > target) {
                // letters[mid] > target, if letters[mid - 1] <= target answer is letters[mid]
                if(mid - 1 >= 0 && letters[mid - 1] <= target) {
                    return letters[mid];
                }
                right = mid - 1;
            } else {
                // letters[mid] <= target, if letters[mid+1] > target answer is leteers[mid+1]
                if(letters[mid+1] > target) return letters[mid+1];
                left = mid + 1;
            }
        }
        return letters[0];
    }
}
```

