This question took me awhile to understand, but thanks to the leetcode discuss section and amazing folks helping each other here - I was able to figure it out and understand completely.

Explanation to problem: We are given a char array (alphabets lol), and lets suppose all of them are sitting on a round table in non decreasing order or serialwise, 'a' being at the right of 'z'.

So we are supposed to return the most near right neighbour of the given char (target) - which is obviously greater then itself!
and, if not -
Think of it as like - *you will travel the whole circle starting from the right of you and encounter a element present in that array - that will be the first element, right!*

**Code:**

**First Method:** Linear search
Time complexity: O(n)
Explanation: Traverse through whole array and check if there's an element greater than the target, if not return first element. 

```
char nextGreatestLetter(vector<char> &letters, char target)
{
    // brute force
    // O(n)
    // O(1)
    int n = letters.size();
    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++)
    {
        if (letters[i] > target)
            return letters[i];
    }
    return letters[0];
}
```

**Second Method:** Binary search
Time complexity: O(logn)
Explanation: Apply binary search to find the index of the element greater to target, return the index in by using modulo arithmetic (letters [low % n], if there no such index exists, then low pointer will become equal to size of array, and n%n=0, so it will return first element of array.

```
char nextGreatestLetter(vector<char> &letters, char target)
{
    // optimized
    // binary search
    // O(logn)
    // O(1)
    int n = letters.size();
    int low = 0, hi = n - 1;
    while (low <= hi)
    {
        int mid = low + (hi - low) / 2;
        if (letters[mid] > target)
            hi = mid - 1;
        else
            low = mid + 1;
    }

    // if (low == n) then return letters[0]
    // else return letters[low]
    return letters[low % n];
}
```

**Third Method:** Using C++ STL 
Time complexity: O(logn)
Explanation: Use C++ upper bound function, as the array is already sorted, it will give the next greater element if it exists in the array or first element if it doesn't.

```
char nextGreatestLetter(vector<char> &letters, char target)
{
    // using STL
    // O(logn)
    // O(1)
    auto it = upper_bound(letters.begin(), letters.end(), target);
    return it == letters.end() ? letters[0] : *it;
}
```

