# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
- Go for traditional `Binary Search` 

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
- Here we need to find the `char` which is is `lexicographically` greater than `target` 
- `lexicography` is a simple increasing order of `char` or `numbers` etc.
- Here it is predefined in question that if no char is found just return the `start` char, so we will initialize `char ans = letters[0]`
- Now apply the simple `binary approach` initialize `mid` inside `while` loop
- If the `target` is less than the `mid` than `ans = letters[mid]` (visualise this by using any static example)
- Now for `target >= mid` we will simplly update `start = mid + 1`
- Finally return the `ans`

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
`O(n)`


# Code
```
class Solution {
    public char nextGreatestLetter(char[] letters, char target) {

        char ans = letters[0];
        int start = 0;
        int end = letters.length - 1;

        while(start <= end){
            int mid = start + (end - start) / 2;

            if(target < letters[mid]){
                ans = letters[mid];
                end = mid - 1;
            }
            else{
                start = mid + 1;
            }
        }
        return ans;
    }
}
```
