# **Statement of the Problem:**

you are given some sorted `letters` and you want to return the smallest letter that is greater than `target`

# **Remark about upper_bound function:** 

the built-in function `upper_bound(first iterator, last iterator, target)`
- is used to return the iterator of the smallest object greater than the `target`
- by dereferencing you will know the value of this iterator
- be careful, the objects which is used to search for must be sorted 
- if the target not found the function will return the last iterator

# **Explanination:**

when you call the function for the target character it will return 2 possible things

1. if there exist character that is the smallest one greater than the target, the function will return iterator points to this charcter
2. otherwise it will return last iterator, in this case we will wrap around for the first character in the `letters` vector which we can access it easily by `letters[0]`

```
class Solution {
public:
    char nextGreatestLetter(vector<char>& letters, char target) {
        auto it = upper_bound(letters.begin(), letters.end(), target);
        if (it == letters.end()) return letters[0];
        return *it;
    }
};
```

